{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609040"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16069"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16069"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0.03,0,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63787"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49217"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"10549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63787"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe diarrhoea for three days. Blood gas analysis shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 38 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate: 19 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 140 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride: 108 mmol/L (95-105)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnion gap: 13 mmol/L (8-16)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this acid-base disturbance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metabolic acidosis with normal anion gap","Metabolic acidosis with high anion gap","Compensated respiratory alkalosis","Respiratory acidosis with normal anion gap","Mixed metabolic and respiratory acidosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic acidosis with normal anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E. The pH is low with reduced bicarbonate, indicating metabolic acidosis. The normal anion gap suggests bicarbonate loss rather than acid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic acidosis with high anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E - The anion gap is within normal limits (13 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory acidosis with normal anion gap\u003C/strong\u003E - The partial pressure of carbon dioxide is normal, ruling out primary respiratory causes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed metabolic and respiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no evidence of respiratory component as carbon dioxide is normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompensated respiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E - The primary disorder is clearly metabolic with low pH and bicarbonate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal anion gap metabolic acidosis typically occurs with bicarbonate loss, as seen in diarrhoea or renal tubular acidosis. The normal anion gap indicates chloride rises to maintain electroneutrality as bicarbonate falls.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metabolic acidosis with a normal anion gap is primarily caused by bicarbonate loss from the gastrointestinal tract or kidneys.","Common causes of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis include diarrhoea and renal tubular acidosis."],"references":["Berend K, de Vries Aiko PJ, Gans Rijk OB. Physiological Approach to Assessment of Acid\u2013Base Disturbances. New England Journal of Medicine.371(15):1434-45. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1003327"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49217"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16069"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49217"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T16:30:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T13:17:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8760"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63787"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","s